                <!-- Introduction Section -->
                <div class="edu-section">
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                            <h2>What is Color Vision Deficiency?</h2>
                            <p>Color Vision Deficiency (CVD), commonly referred to as color blindness, affects
                                approximately 1 in 12 men and 1 in 200 women worldwide. It's a condition where
                                individuals have difficulty distinguishing certain colors or perceiving color
                                differences.</p>
                            <p>Most cases of CVD are genetic and present from birth, but some can be acquired through
                                eye diseases, certain medications, or aging. CVD occurs when one or more of the three
                                types of cone cells in the retina (responsible for color perception) are absent or
                                function abnormally.</p>
                            <p>While "color blindness" is a common term, true color blindness (seeing only in shades of
                                gray) is extremely rare. Most people with CVD can see colors but have difficulty
                                differentiating between particular color pairs.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-md-6">
                            <div class="card h-100">
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <h4 class="card-title">Key Facts About CVD</h4>
                                    <ul class="mt-3">
                                        <li>Affects approximately 8% of men and 0.5% of women worldwide</li>
                                        <li>Most commonly inherited on the X chromosome (explaining higher prevalence in
                                            males)</li>
                                        <li>Cannot be "cured" but can be managed with assistive technologies</li>
                                        <li>Severity varies widely between individuals</li>
                                        <li>Red-green color deficiency is the most common form</li>
                                        <li>May impact career choices in fields requiring precise color discrimination
                                        </li>
                                        <li>Often undiagnosed in children until they face difficulties with color-coded
                                            materials</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Types of CVD Section -->
                <div class="edu-section">
                    <h2 class="mb-4">Types of Color Vision Deficiency</h2>
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="col-lg-4 mb-4">
                            <div class="card h-100">
                                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                                    <h3 class="card-title mb-0">Protanopia</h3>
                                </div>
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <p>Protanopia is caused by the absence or dysfunction of red-sensitive photoreceptor
                                        (L-cone) cells in the retina.</p>
                                    <h5>Characteristics:</h5>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Difficulty distinguishing between red and green colors</li>
                                        <li>Reds appear darker than normal and may look black</li>
                                        <li>Greens appear more beige/yellow</li>
                                        <li>Reduced overall brightness of red, orange, and yellow</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="mt-3">
                                        <h5>Normal Vision vs. Protanopia</h5>
                                        <div class="cvd-comparison">
                                            <div class="image-container">

                                                <img src="/images/ntop.png" alt="Normal color spectrum"
                                                    class="img-fluid">
                                            </div>

                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="col-lg-4 mb-4">
                            <div class="card h-100">
                                <div class="card-header bg-success text-white">
                                    <h3 class="card-title mb-0">Deuteranopia</h3>
                                </div>
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <p>Deuteranopia occurs when green-sensitive photoreceptor (M-cone) cells are absent
                                        or dysfunctional.</p>
                                    <h5>Characteristics:</h5>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Difficulty distinguishing between red and green colors</li>
                                        <li>Greens appear more reddish</li>
                                        <li>Reds may appear as brownish-yellow</li>
                                        <li>Normal brightness perception (unlike protanopia)</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="mt-3">
                                        <h5>Normal Vision vs. Deuteranopia</h5>
                                        <div class="cvd-comparison">
                                            <div class="image-container">

                                                <img src="/images/ntod.png" alt="Normal color spectrum"
                                                    class="img-fluid">
                                            </div>

                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="col-lg-4 mb-4">
                            <div class="card h-100">
                                <div class="card-header bg-info text-white">
                                    <h3 class="card-title mb-0">Tritanopia</h3>
                                </div>
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <p>Tritanopia is a rare condition resulting from absent or dysfunctional
                                        blue-sensitive photoreceptor (S-cone) cells.</p>
                                    <h5>Characteristics:</h5>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Difficulty distinguishing between blue and yellow colors</li>
                                        <li>Blues appear greenish</li>
                                        <li>Yellows appear reddish or pink</li>
                                        <li>Can be acquired through aging or certain medications</li>
                                    </ul>
                                    <div class="mt-3">
                                        <h5>Normal Vision vs. Tritanopia</h5>
                                        <div class="cvd-comparison">
                                            <div class="image-container">

                                                <img src="/images/ntot.png" alt="Normal color spectrum"
                                                    class="img-fluid">
                                            </div>

                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- How ChromaVision Works Section -->
                <div class="edu-section">
                    <h2 class="mb-4">How ChromaVision Works</h2>
                    <div class="row">
                        <div class="col-lg-7">
                            <p>ChromaVision uses advanced color transformation algorithms to enhance and correct images
                                for people with color vision deficiency. The application processes images through the
                                following steps:</p>

                            <div class="card mb-4">
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <h5>1. Color Space Transformation</h5>
                                    <p>Images are first converted from standard RGB color space to LMS color space,
                                        which represents colors based on the response of the three types of cone cells
                                        in the human eye (Long, Medium, and Short wavelengths).</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="card mb-4">
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <h5>2. Deficiency Simulation</h5>
                                    <p>For educational purposes, ChromaVision can simulate how images appear to
                                        individuals with different types of CVD by applying scientifically validated
                                        transformation matrices that map normal vision to CVD vision.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="card mb-4">
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <h5>3. Daltonization Process</h5>
                                    <p>The core correction mechanism, known as "daltonization," redistributes colors
                                        that are indistinguishable to people with CVD to colors they can perceive. This
                                        process:</p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Identifies problematic color combinations</li>
                                        <li>Shifts these colors to enhance contrast and distinguishability</li>
                                        <li>Preserves overall image appearance while making key details visible</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="card">
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <h5>4. Personalized Calibration</h5>
                                    <p>ChromaVision allows users to adjust correction intensity to match their specific
                                        needs, as CVD varies in severity between individuals. The application saves
                                        these preferences for future use.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-lg-5">
                            <div class="card">
                                <div class="card-body">
                                    <h4 class="card-title">Color Transformation Matrix</h4>
                                    <p>Below is an example of the transformation matrix used for Deuteranopia
                                        correction:</p>
                                    <pre class="bg-light p-3 rounded">
// LMS to RGB Transformation
